headline: Planemaker Boeing swings to quarterly profit on unit sale
summary:
STORY: Boeing swung to a fourth-quarter profit on Tuesday (January 27)

The planemaker said it was driven by the sale of its navigation software services provider.

And by rising jet output and stronger deliveries.

Although the company also recorded a $565 million charge on a tanker program.

That was due to higher estimated production support and supply chain costs.

The planemaker scored a net profit of $8.22 billion for the quarter through December.

That was way up on a loss of $3.86 billion a year earlier.

The quarterly results included the $10.6 billion of its Jeppesen unit.

Boeing's fourth-quarter revenue rose 57% to just under $24 billion - ahead of expectations.

The firm also increased output of its two most popular jetliners - the 737 MAX and 787.

And it continued to resolve quality problems which have caused delivery delays over the last few years.

Boeing's commerical airplane unit still posted a quarterly loss of $632 million despite production improvements.

The firm delivered 600 airliners last year across all jet programs - its most in seven years.

It marked a largely positive update for a company beset by the 737 MAX scandal, supply chain issues and quality problems in recent years.

headline: UPS Retires MD-11 Jets From Fleet
summary: United Parcel Service said it has retired its fleet of MD-11 jets after a deadly crash near its Louisville cargo hub in November.  UPS said Tuesday that it had pulled forward plans to modernize its aircraft fleet and finished the MD-11 retirements by the end of last year.  Chief Executive Carol Tomé said the company would replace much of the capacity provided by MD-11s with Boeing 767 planes over the next year or so.

content.title: UPS Retires MD-11 Jets From Fleet
content.summary: United Parcel Service said it has retired its fleet of MD-11 jets after a deadly crash near its Louisville cargo hub in November.  UPS said Tuesday that it had pulled forward plans to modernize its aircraft fleet and finished the MD-11 retirements by the end of last year.  Chief Executive Carol Tomé said the company would replace much of the capacity provided by MD-11s with Boeing 767 planes over the next year or so.
